  "prompt": "I have a dandruff problem. I wash my hair every other day, which makes my hair dry. If not washed, my scalp becomes oily, and dandruff and hair loss increase. What should I do?",
  "response": "Dealing with dandruff, dry hair, and an oily scalp can be challenging, but there are multiple strategies you can consider to help manage these issues:\n\n1. **Choose the Right Shampoo**: Look for a mild, sulfate-free shampoo if your hair is dry. Consider using a medicated shampoo that contains active ingredients like zinc pyrithione, ketoconazole, salicylic acid, or selenium sulfide for dandruff treatment. You can alternate between a medicated shampoo and a moisturizing one to help balance your scalp condition.\n\n2. **Moisturize Your Scalp**: After washing, consider using a lightweight conditioner on your scalp and hair. You might also try scalp oils or treatments containing tea tree oil or argan oil, but use them sparingly to avoid making your hair greasy.\n\n3. **Adjust Washing Frequency**: If washing every other day is drying your hair, you might want to try extending the time between washes. You can use dry shampoo on days when you don\u2019t wash your hair to help absorb excess oil and keep your hair looking fresh.\n\n4. **Hydration and Diet**: Ensure you are well-hydrated and maintain a balanced diet rich in omega-3 fatty acids, vitamins (especially B vitamins and vitamin E), and minerals that promote scalp health.\n\n5. **Manage Stress**: Stress can exacerbate dandruff and hair loss. Consider stress-reducing techniques such as yoga, meditation, or regular exercise.\n\n6. **Avoid Styling Products**: Try to minimize the use of hair styling products, as they can accumulate on the scalp and exacerbate dandruff.\n\n7. **See a Dermatologist**: If over-the-counter treatments don't help, it may be a good idea to consult a dermatologist. They can provide personalized recommendations, and if necessary, prescription treatments.\n\n8. **Scalp Care**: Consider incorporating scalp massages into your routine. This can help promote circulation and might alleviate some of the buildup on your scalp.\n\nTransitioning your hair care routine can take time, so be patient and monitor how your scalp and hair respond to any changes you make.",
